  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at preventing money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- Provides international standards for combating money laundering\n- 40 recommendations widely adopted by countries globally\n\n2. United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Requires member states to criminalize money laundering\n- Promotes international cooperation in investigating financial crimes\n\n3. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision Guidelines\n- Establishes principles for preventing criminal use of banking systems\n\n4. The Egmont Group\n- International network of financial intelligence units\n- Facilitates information sharing to combat money laundering\n\n5. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Provide regulations for EU member states\n- Continually updated to address emerging financial risks\n\n6. Bank Secrecy Act (US) and similar national laws\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Help track and prevent money laundering activities\n\nThese international frameworks encourage countries to implement domestic laws and regulations to detect, prevent, and prosecute money laundering activities.",
